{
  "name": "Bhai Tarlochan Singh (Delhi)",
  "url": "https://kirtansewa.net/index.php/bhai-tarlochan-singh-delhi/",
  "image_url": "https://cdn.kirtansewa.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/22012647/20130507_004edit.jpg",
  "body": [
    "Bhai Tarlochan Singh was born in 1929 in the village of Garaya Wala, near Rawalpindi, in present day Pakistan. His father, Bhai Dyal Singh, was also a Kirtani, and introduced him to Kirtan from a very young age. At the tender age of two, he began learning the basics of music and Kirtan under the guidance of Master Waryam Singh of Gujranwala, from whom he trained under for many years.",
    "Bhai Tarlochan Singh began performing Kirtan in 1942 alongside his father, until the passing of Bhai Dyal Singh in December 1955. They captivated the ‘Sangat’ of Gujranwala for many years with their soul stirring Kirtan. Following the traumatic Partition of Punjab in 1947, they relocated and continued performing Kirtan in Amritsar, preserving this tradition amidst the upheaval. After the passing of his father, Bhai Tarlochan Singh carried forward the family legacy by forming his own ‘jatha’ with his brothers, Bhai Kartar Singh and Bhai Manmohan Singh.",
    "In May 1967, they joined the Delhi Gurdwara Parbandhak Committee and began performing regularly at various Gurdwaras in Delhi. Over time, Bhai Tarlochan Singh became well known across India for his melodious Kirtan. His growing popularity led to invitations to perform Kirtan in many parts of the country, as well as internationally. He travelled to countries such as Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore, and the United States to share Kirtan with Sikh communities abroad.",
    "Throughout his career, many of his Kirtan recordings were released by different studios. Around 30 audio cassettes of his work were produced, including recitations of Japji Sahib, Anand Sahib, Rehras Sahib, Sukhmani Sahib, and numerous Kirtan tracks. He also participated in the recording of several notable Kirtan albums, including one marking the 500th birth anniversary of Guru Nanak Dev Ji, the 300th anniversary of the martyrdom of Guru Tegh Bahadur Sahib Ji, and the first Parkash Purab of Guru Granth Sahib Ji.",
    "Bhai Tarlochan Singh dedicated his life to singing Gurbani and serving the Sikh community through his Kirtan."
  ],
